{{Confucianism}}
'''Confucian ritual religion''' ([[Simplified Chinese|s]] 礼教, [[Traditional Chinese|t]] 禮教 ''Lǐjiào'', "rites' transmission", also called 名教 ''Míngjiào'', the "names' transmission"), or the '''Confucian civil religion''',{{sfnb|Dessein|2014}} defines the [[civil religion]] of [[China]]. It consists in the state-endorsed ceremonies and sacrifices ([[cult (religious practice)|cults]]), held according to [[Confucianism|Confucian]] modalities, dedicated to those gods which represent the [[Chinese theology|theologico]]-political origin of the state itself and the Chinese civilisation.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|pp=173-174}} These rituals have undergone a great revitalisation in post-Maoist China creating a public space in which the Chinese state and popular Confucian movements jostle and negotiate with each other.{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|pp=173-174}}

Worship of cosmological gods and of [[Confucius]],{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2009}}{{sfnb|Billioud|Thoraval|2015|pp=173-174}} is carried out regularly at [[Chinese temple|consecrated public spaces]]

