{{Italic title}} '''''Contradictio in adiecto''''' is [[Latin]] [[Etymology|for]] "a contradiction between parts of an argument" (''adiectum'' "brought about, brought forward"). It differs from a "contradiction in terms", which refers to two contradictory words normally appearing together, e.g., "cold heat". It is "the characteristic denoted by the adjective stands in contrast to the noun." <ref name="Basic Rhetorics Tropes web site">[http://www.as.uni-heidelberg.de/projekte/rhetorics/tropes.html Basic Rhetorics Tropes web site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830094804/http://www.as.uni-heidelberg.de/projekte/rhetorics/tropes.html |date=2007-08-30 }}</ref> ==See also== * [[List of legal Latin terms]] * [[Oxymoron]] * [[Rhetoric]] * [[Wooden iron]]
